--------------------<>-------------------------<>---------------------

<|> 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞𝐬 -->  It is a container that store value in a Python program.
                  In another word ,, Variables are place holder for storing data.

                     Example --> value = 10 
                             ( 'Value' is a variable and hold data '10'.)

-------------------<>--------------------------<>-----------------------

<|> 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐄𝐱𝐩𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 <|>

       >> 𝑽𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝑵𝒂𝒎𝒆 --> A label for memory location.

       >> 𝑽𝒂𝒍𝒖𝒆 --> The value or data that would stored in variables.

       >> 𝑺𝒕𝒐𝒓𝒂𝒈𝒆 --> A place where data can be stored.

       >> 𝑫𝒆𝒄𝒍𝒂𝒓𝒂𝒕𝒊𝒐𝒏 --> Announce a variable usually when begins your program. (When you explain variable).

--------------------------<>---------------------------------<>----------------------------

<|> 𝐍𝐚𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐨𝐟 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞𝐬 <|>
       A set of rules for naming a Python variables.

          >> A variable name must start with a letter , underscore character.
          >> A variable cannot start with a number.
          >> A variable name can only contain alpha-numeric characters and underscore ( 0-9 , A - z and _ ).
          >> Variable name are case sensitive ( Age , age , AGE - Different three variable).

            -- Example of Variables --

        <> 𝑽𝒂𝒍𝒊𝒅 𝑽𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝑵𝒂𝒎𝒆𝒔 ---> 

               :: Valid_num = 10   / Valid_Num = 10
               :: valid_num = 20   / valid_Num = 20
               :: _Validnum = 30
               :: Validnum1 = 40
               :: validnum2 = 50
               :: valid = 10    /  Valid = 10

         <> 𝑼𝒏𝒗𝒂𝒍𝒊𝒅 𝑽𝒂𝒓𝒊𝒂𝒃𝒍𝒆𝒔 𝑵𝒂𝒎𝒆𝒔 ---> 
           
               :: 1Valid_num = 10 
               :: 2validnum = 20 
               :: 3_Validnum = 30

------------------------<>---------------------------------------<>-------------------------

<|>  𝐌𝐮𝐥𝐭𝐢𝐩𝐥𝐞 𝐯𝐚𝐥𝐮𝐞 𝐭𝐨 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞  <|>
         
        ::> You can assign one value to several variables at the same time.
      𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >>    a = b = c = 10
                 print(a + b)            #output = 20
                 print(a * b)            #output = 100
                 print(a + b + c)        #output = 30

        ::> You can also assign different values to different variables in the same command.
      𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >>   a , b , c = 10 , 20 , 30
                print(a + b)         #output = 30
                print(a + b + c)     #output = 60
                print(a * c)         #output = 300

        ::> You can use this method to swap the values of two variables.
      𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >>   a , b = 10 , 20
                x , y = b , a
                print(a , b)        #output = 10 , 20
                print(x , y)        #output = 20 , 10


------------------------<>---------------------------------------<>-------------------------

<|>  𝐋𝐨𝐜𝐚𝐥 & 𝐆𝐥𝐨𝐛𝐚𝐥 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞𝐬  <|>

       <::> 𝙇𝙤𝙘𝙖𝙡 𝙑𝙖𝙧𝙞𝙖𝙗𝙡𝙚𝙨 -->>
                Local variables are defined inside a function or a block of code and can only be accessed from that
                specific function or block.

            𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >>     def my_fun():
                               local_var = 10
                               print(local_var)      #output = 10
                         my_fun()

       <::> 𝙂𝙡𝙤𝙗𝙖𝙡 𝙑𝙖𝙧𝙞𝙖𝙗𝙡𝙚𝙨 -->>
                 It is defined outside any function and can be accessed from any part of the program.
    
          𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >> 1.    global_var = 20
                         def out_fun():
                               print("inside" , global_var)      #output = 20
                         out_fun()
                               print("ouside" , global_var)      #output = 20

          𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >> 2.    def f():
                             print("inside" , s)

                        s = "Hello , Python"
                        f()
                           print("outside" , s)    

------------------------<>---------------------------------------<>-------------------------

<|> 𝐃𝐞𝐥𝐞𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐕𝐚𝐫𝐢𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 -->>
        Deleting a variable involves removing it from memory, which can do by 'del' statement. 
             
           𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 >>      x = 10
                          print(x)   # Output: 10
                        del x
                          print(x)   # Raises NameError: name 'x' is not defined



